  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Statement.}\nConsistency between micro and macro descriptions requires that ensemble averages of quantum observables satisfy classical conservation laws and equations of motion when decoherence is effective.\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Equation.}\n\\begin{equation}\n\\frac{\\mathrm{d}}{\\mathrm{d}t}\\langle A\\rangle\n=\n\\left\\langle\n\\frac{i}{\\hbar}[H,A]\n+\n\\frac{\\partial A}{\\partial t}\n\\right\\rangle .\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Classical Limit Condition.}\n\\begin{equation}\n\\langle A\\rangle\n\\longrightarrow\nA_{\\mathrm{cl}} .\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\nFor a quantum observable $A$, the expectation value evolves by the Heisenberg equation:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\frac{\\mathrm{d}}{\\mathrm{d}t}\\langle A\\rangle\n=\n\\left\\langle\n\\frac{i}{\\hbar}[H,A]\n+\n\\frac{\\partial A}{\\partial t}\n\\right\\rangle .\n\\end{equation}\n\nWhen decoherence suppresses interference, expectation values behave as classical ensemble variables:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\langle A\\rangle\n\\rightarrow\nA_{\\mathrm{cl}}.\n\\end{equation}\n\nMacro-consistency requires that these limiting variables satisfy the corresponding classical equations:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\boxed{\n\\mathcal{E}_{\\mathrm{macro}}(A_{\\mathrm{cl}})=0 .\n}\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\nThe micro-to-macro bridge is valid when quantum expectation values reproduce classical conservation and motion laws in the decohered limit.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
